pull_request.title: Implement build-push workflow for Aliyun Container Registry with latest stable GitHub Actions
pull_request.body:
This PR implements a new GitHub Actions workflow `build-push.yml` that builds and pushes Docker images to Aliyun Container Registry when changes are pushed to the main branch.

## Key Features

- **Automatic triggering**: Activates on pushes to `main` branch and supports manual dispatch
- **Conditional building**: Uses file change detection to only build when `api/**` or workflow files are modified
- **Latest stable actions**: Updates all GitHub Actions to their newest stable versions for improved security and performance
- **Registry integration**: Seamlessly integrates with Aliyun Container Registry using environment variables and secrets

## Technical Implementation

The workflow consists of two main jobs:

1. **Change Detection**: Uses `dorny/paths-filter@v3` to detect relevant file changes
2. **Build and Push**: Conditionally builds and pushes the API Docker image using the latest Docker actions

## Action Version Updates

All GitHub Actions have been updated to their latest stable versions:
- `actions/checkout@v3` ‚Üí `@v4`
- `docker/setup-buildx-action@v2` ‚Üí `@v3` 
- `docker/login-action@v2` ‚Üí `@v3`
- `docker/metadata-action@v4` ‚Üí `@v5`
- `docker/build-push-action@v4` ‚Üí `@v6`
- `dorny/paths-filter@v2` ‚Üí `@v3`

## Environment Configuration

The workflow requires the following environment variables to be configured in the repository:

**Repository Variables:**
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY` - Aliyun container registry URL
- `API_IMAGE_NAME` - Target image name

**Repository Secrets:**
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY_USER` - Registry username
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY_PWD` - Registry password

## Workflow Relationship

This new workflow complements the existing `only-build.yml` workflow:
- `only-build.yml`: Builds (but doesn't push) on non-main branches
- `build-push.yml`: Builds and pushes on main branch

This ensures a complete CI/CD pipeline where feature branches are validated through build-only testing, while the main branch automatically deploys to the container registry.

Fixes #46.

issue.title: tasks outputs that dependent tasks can read from
issue.body:
### Description

# Usecase

Consider a setup where many tasks needs same credentials for different operations.

Therefore, the logical thing is to have a task that reads from some secret manager creds that must not be preserved on disk, and passes them **in-memory** to all its dependents.

# Current state
The only way I could find how to do it now - is have the "reader" task print something that the downstream stasks have to pass to eval - e.g. a step like `- eval $(task creds)`.

```
version: '3'

tasks:
  creds:
    cmds:
    - echo "export USR=me; export PWD=shhhh!!!;"
   
  operation1:
    cmds:
    - >
       eval $(task creds)
       some-cli-tool -u $USR -p $PWD some operation1

  operation2:
    deps: [creds]
    cmds:
    - >
       eval $(task creds)
       some-cli-tool -u $USR -p $PWD some operation2
```

That is less than ideal, first because it is platform-dependent and shell dependent. second - if I want to debug something - I should print it to `>&2` - and that's also a shell specific thing. third - the `eval` must happen on every command - it is not persisted even on the task level... If I want to pass it to env - it gets very clunky:

```
tasks:
  creds:
    cmds:
    - echo '{"USR":"me","PWD":"shhhh!!!;"}'
   
  operation1:
    vars:
       USR:  { sh: task creds | jq.USR }
       PWD:  { sh: task creds | jq.PWD}
    cmds:
    - >
       some-cli-tool-expects-ENV-vars operation3
```
this negates all the reuse beause the `operation<#>.vars` is coppied between all the operations that depend on `creds` :( 

# Proposal

I would propose tasks to have `outputs`, similar to how outputs work in github actions, just less cumbersome...

e.g:
```
version: '3'

tasks:
  creds:
    vars:
      JSON:
        sh: aws sts ....
      USR: 
        sh: echo {{.JSON}} | jq .USR
        exports: true  #makes it available on context of dependent tasks
      PWD: 
        sh: echo {{.JSON}} | jq .PWD
        exports: { as: SVC_API_KEY } # makes it exported as `SVC_API_KEY`

  operation1:
    deps: [creds]
    cmds:
    - some-cli-tool -u $USR some operation1
```
Mind that on `operation1` - it explicitly uses `$USR` and not `{{.USR}}` so that the value is not spat to screen.

It would be nice to support secrets:
```
  creds:
    vars:
      JSON:
        sh: aws sts ....
      USR: 
        sh: echo {{.JSON}} | jq .USR
        exports: true  # make it available on contexts of dependent tasks
      PWD:
         sh: echo {{.JSON}} | jq .PWD
         exports: true
         secret: true  # masks the secret from being print 
```
but that can be dealt in another feature

issue.title: Support dbt 1.10
issue.body:
I want to support dbt v1.10. dbt v1.10 changed the schema on the `meta` configs. So, we probably need some changes on the side of dbt-osmosis as well.

https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/dbt-versions/core-upgrade/upgrading-to-v1.10

Specifically, we may want to discuss the compatibility in the different schemas.

- Plan A: We will have the backward compatibility for dbt 1.9 or earlier. 
    - Pros:
        - dbt users which uses dbt 1.9 or earlier will keep using newer versions of dbt-osmosis in the future. 
    - Cons:
        - Supporting the two different schemas might be hassle. 
- Plan B: We will focus on only dbt 1.10 or later. 
    - Pros:
        - The implementation will be simpler than Plan A.
    - Cons:
        - dbt 1.9 or earlier don't perfectly work,.

comment.body: @z3z1ma I want to discuss how to support the new schema introduced by dbt 1.10, because the end of life of dbt 1.9 is planed on Dec 8, 2025. I am wondering if we should implement complicated multiple version support for the deprecating version. I can technically implement the backward compatibility for dbt 1.9 or earlier aside from the new schema for dbt 1.10. I was faced with a similar situation in `yu-iskw/dbt-artifacts-parser` to support pydantic v1 and v2. I after all decided not to support both versions in a version. I stopped supporting pydantic v1, because it has been sunsetting. Instead, I offered two versions of `dbt-artifacts-perser` for pydantic v1 and v2 with the same functionality respectively. In that way, we can take plan B, though we offers the same functionality for dbt 1.9 or earlier and dbt 1.10. What do you think? https://github.com/yu-iskw/dbt-artifacts-parser?tab=readme-ov-file#supported-versions-and-compatibility
